description:
As a 6-issue magazine series published by Fantagraphics, Street Music offered "Stories & Features from the Real World." Created by Mark Burbey in 1988, during the heyday of black-&-white autobiographical and realistic comics, most, if not all, of the content was rooted in real life subjects and concerns. The cornerstone of the magazine was the eponymous 6-part story by Burbey and artist Bili Turner. Regular contributors included Richard Sala, Rich Larson, Angela Bocage, and Dave Marshall, with Justin Green, Lloyd Dangle, Colin Upton, Richard G. Taylor, Mark Askwith, Michael Kraiger, John MacLeod, Dan Seitler, Mark Martin, George Metzger, Scott Deschaine, and Patricia Jeres. Street Music was one of the first anthologies to publish the work of Carol Tyler, and her regular feature, "Job Abuse," which was later collected into the volume, Job Thing. Covers are by Richard Sala, Chester Brown, Guy Colwell, and Gilbert Hernandez.

The title logo was designed by Michael Cherkas.
name: Street Music
